U.S.: Rehearsal is the Mother of Wisdom
It even becomes comical, the assiduous effort with which Barack Obama, president with a reputation for wisdom, reproduces the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghan question, which he himself considered as very simple.
When he finally let his long-awaited doctrine perspire, it turned out that he had copied it to carbon paper since Bush’s Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not content with using the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text, he did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's speech of January 2007 as the title of his own speech: "A new road forward".
At the same time, he personally criticized Bush’s idea of sending new reinforcements to a civil war-ravaged Iraq as “irresponsible and a catastrophic decision in its consequences.”
The months that followed, however, showed that Bush's strategy, which emanated from the recommendations of the campaign commanders, was the only one possible and likely to be so successful that the newspapers at present do not speak at all of Iraq.
This did not improve Bush's reputation, that is, objectively speaking, it left his successor in a much more favorable final situation than one could hope.
Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again in Afghanistan
It was again campaign commanders who asked him for an increase in the military contingent, notably the commander of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who even severely criticized the reluctance of the White House despite the habits of subordination.
He asked for 40,000 men in order to make the situation more favorable.
The president hesitated for three months but for lack of a better option, he at least deceived the 10,000-strong general.
He succeeded in extracting the promise of an additional 5,000 from Europe, even though he originally counted on 10,000.
What brings the most problems in all of Obama’s strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies from Afghanistan within 18 months and complete this whole process within three years.
Many doubt that a halving increase will bear the same fruits as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honor the agreements.
The Afghan situation stands out because of the exact opposite - no one can be counted on and no treaties are respected.
In these circumstances, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing leaders on a day-to-day basis as they see fit.
Political institutions, although formally founded, will remain only powder in the eyes behind which patriarchal ethnic relations will proliferate.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of the various ethnic groups in view of the lack of clarity in relation to relations, which are further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a “prompt to act state,” which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is perplexed by its voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and it is now on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic and out-of-reality heart can be persuaded that the little soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for their "prompt return home" will bring there a real miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect confession of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in military operations in Afghanistan is moving towards the negative.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how security in Germany or Italy is linked to a war in the mountains of Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically altering the situation is the evolution of events related to Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the tightened sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the Americans will find themselves faced with the very difficult question of solving the problem through the use of military force.
It will have to be responded to, for example, at a time when, according to Obama, America will come to the victorious withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
Any such solution, however, will lead to a dramatic reversal of the Afghan situation.
Obama’s only blurb is the fact that he has three years until the presidential election and therefore there is still enough time for him to work on a new strategy, in case it turns out to be a total fiasco.
