However, it is possible to radically extend the life of patients through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their consumption leads to a number of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses on which the drugs no longer have an effect.
The work of experts from three institutions, the Czech Academy of Sciences, V<0xC5><0xA0>CHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg paves the way for a way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metallocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
The metallocarboranes are an assembly of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way than all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The researchers' work leads them to discover new "improved" substances, based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings on virus proteins.
The metallocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two cages with multiple walls are formed by the atoms of boron, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
Without the division of the HIV virus caused by HIV protease there would be no birth of mature infectious particles of the virus.
If the protease of HIV is stopped, the spread of the virus in the patient's body will also be stopped, the researchers explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In their work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe a series of combinations where two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic link, which is then systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The efficacy of this series of substances on HIV proteases was tested in test specimens as well as on its resistant variants, obtained from HIV-infected patients.
On the current version of the enzyme, the effect of metallocarborans is not as strong as on clinical drugs, however, it does not weaken on the resistant versions against which common drugs are often ineffective.
The metallocarboranes, with their unique mechanism of action and other properties such as their biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications are therefore interesting combinations to be further examined to move towards the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína <0xC5><0x98>ezá<0xC4><0x8D>ová, director of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biology.
