A gradual mitigation
Written in the country's 1978 constitution, China's one-child policy is to date, without question, the most controversial obligation introduced by the communist government.
Couples who break this policy may face huge fines -- up to three times their annual income -- and discrimination in the workplace.
Chinese authorities have given the police a duty to help the country avoid a dangerous trend for its natural resources, while human rights lawyers have denounced abuses in the execution of this policy.
In rural areas, some officials forced pregnant women with a second child to have an abortion.
In addition, many couples have resorted to selective abortions leading to an abnormally high boys-to-girls ratio.
In recent years, the population authorities have gradually softened their position on the one-child policy.
