It gives great flexibility to the process, said John Coequyt, Representative in Washington of the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, studied a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what UN Executive Secretary-General on climate change Yvo de Boer described as the “full picture.”
It shows the guidelines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 2020, by 25 to 45 percent from 1990 levels, while major developing countries, over the same period, would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by between 50 and 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also relaunched talks on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change -- to withstand floods and drought or to avoid deforestation.
However, on Friday, the same verbal altercations occurred, which have dominated negotiations since last week.
Todd Stern, the U.S. representative to the climate negotiation, rejected any discussion requiring the reduction of greenhouse gases by industrialized countries, compared to the voluntary efforts made by major emerging economies, if these were not financed by developed countries.
