Some of these countries more vulnerable to the impact of climate change have indicated that they will continue to press for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the key participants say the negotiations will lead to a minimum, political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, head of the European Commission’s climate unit, said the action of small island states had “put political pressure on the full political process,” partly because they are now unified and calling on emerging economies such as China and India to act.
