But on Friday evening, the office of the UDF association, controlled by the friends of François Bayrou who do not intend to be dispossessed, came out of its silence to launch a letter of formal notice to the minister and the deputy, advising them not to use the acronym and to pass on ownership of the brand, under penalty of legal proceedings.
In recent days, you have multiplied the statements indicating that you would propose to your political movement to "retake" the acronym UDF, writes the association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the bureau, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez of the MoDem, as well as Senator Jean Arthuis of the centrist Alliance.
You also thought it good to have the name of this movement, the "New Centre", the slogan "Today's UDF", posted on your militant material and on the front page of your site, also note the signatories of the letter.
As you know, you have no right to use this acronym, explains the UDF office, which urges the NC to remove "immediately the mention of the name of the UDF from any medium as well as (its) website".
He also asks Hervé de Charette "to pass on the ownership of (the) mark to its legitimate successors."
If you did not, the courts would be seized to enforce the law and the legitimate rights of the members of the UDF, warn the signatories.
In their letter, they specify that the UDF "is a political movement in its own right since 1978" and recall that Mr Morin and his friends had "made the choice" to leave him in 2007 "to create a competing movement, as others had done in 2002, to create the UMP".
The New Centre therefore has, in their view, no right to use the acronym UDF (Union for French Democracy).
They also recall that the last congress of the UDF voted in 2007 to join the MoDem for three years and the creation of an office charged with defending "the material and moral interests" of the formation founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the office continues, "when he filed the trademark", he was "no longer a member of the UDF for three years", but at the UMP.
He outrageously and fraudulently takes advantage of the absence of filing the acronym UDF to perform it on his behalf.
This indelicacy is turning into a crime, they denounce, before ironizing on the strategy of the NC: "It seems to us that in politics, as in life, it is more worthy to make a name for yourself than to try to get out of anonymity by fraudulently taking a name to which one is not entitled".
Liliane Bettencourt case: François-Marie Banier to be tried for abuse of weakness
The court of Nanterre decided on Friday to judge the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine whether, as accused by the daughter of billionaire Liliane Bettencourt, he took advantage of a state of weakness of the octogenarian to rob her of part of her fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his photographs of stars, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010 for abuse of weakness, a crime punishable by up to three years in prison and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will be a trial in this case worthy of a saga about one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter tear each other apart while holding the reins of the L'Oréal cosmetics empire.
But the 15th correctional chamber also ordered that a medical assessment of Liliane Bettencourt, 87, should be conducted collegiately by three doctors.
The heiress and main shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to submit to such an examination, in any case not under the conditions proposed by the Nanterre prosecutor's office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will have to submit a report by March 10, 2010, stating in particular if Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a weak state and at what periods.
I think she'll submit to it.
I'm going to talk to him about it," Mrs. Bettencourt's lawyer, Georges Kiejman, said after the hearing.
Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers’ lawyer, Olivier Metzner, welcomed the court’s decision.
This is excellent news (...) Expertise will show that he (Mr. Banier) manipulated this elderly lady who must be protected, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt’s only daughter has filed criminal charges against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and artist who she accuses of taking advantage of her mother’s weakness for years to obtain a billion euros in donations, in the form of cheques, life insurance contracts or master paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always refuted being manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a longtime friend.
While the court had to examine the admissibility of the action brought by Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers' pleas sometimes turned to the big family unpacking on Friday.
Thus, Liliane Bettencourt’s lawyer reported three letters sent by her client (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) to her notary, in which she said she was suspicious of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers’ husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "Could you explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier once, twice a day for fifteen years.
“Françoise, I haven’t been able to talk to her since her marriage.”
For its part, the Nanterre prosecutor's office again ruled that the complainant was inadmissible to act, especially since a guardianship judge refused in recent days to grant her request to open a judicial protection procedure for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to act in court, she is not under protection and has no guardian.
No one else has to act in his place," said prosecutor Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
The court ultimately decided that it would rule once the trial took place on the admissibility of Ms. Bettencourt-Meyers.
Management revolution or the end of economic intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been in vain...
For more than a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies towards its employees, recalls the position of companies vis-à-vis consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about making employees adhere to "values" determined from above as it was once, to impose on consumers products thought by the technicians of the factory.
By putting the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has put the strategies of conquest of the markets back in place... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products disconnected from the factors of customer preferences regularly returns!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects executives in particular.
This demobilization seriously jeopardizes the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, in particular R&D and, even more, economic intelligence.
Indeed, EI "requires from all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a forward-looking vision"; it requires a commitment on the part of employees that the revenues of authoritarian management totally contradict.
That is why we are calling for a managerial revolution that would put employees at the center of the company’s concerns on the same footing as the customer.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its employees – incite this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First, because I have been able to see that, in the face of a new situation, every structure finally manages, after many detours, to do priority... what it has always done.!
Second, because authoritarianism – one of the pathologies of power – grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
Coming from the great schools of engineering, they have a mechanistic interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, out of intellectual comfort, the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the US "neurosciences" and widely disseminated, without their knowledge, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of the engagement of executives, a recent Ipsos survey published in Le Figaro.fr comforts leaders in a mechanistic governance posture, inappropriate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern companies requires adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating, in any reasoning or governance practice, a fundamental observation: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it clearly appears as a means of realizing part of their dreams, their ambitions, their projects.
Currently, only studies from the Motivational Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to realize their life projects.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and put their human resources management "in place".
They thus create a favourable terrain for the concerted development of robust and effective economic intelligence.
Oslo Speech: 'Just War' Worth Right-Wing Praise to Obama
The American right has welcomed the speech delivered the day before in Oslo by Barack Obama, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize has defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The Conservatives, who had brocaded the award for Mr. Obama on October 9, this time applauded the presidential speech, like Sarah Palin, a former vice presidential candidate in the 2008 election.
I liked what he said, said Ms. Palin, a figurehead in the right wing of the Republican Party, to USA Today, adding that she herself addressed the "sometimes necessary" theme of war in her memoirs that have just been published.
War is of course the last thing I think Americans want to do, but it is necessary.
These terrorists must be stopped all over there, she said.
Obama, who inherited his predecessor George W. Bush's two wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, worked Thursday in Oslo to justify the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send an additional 30,000 troops to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, said the president had done a "very good job" in Oslo.
I found that the speech was really very good, welcomed the former Speaker of the House of Representatives, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential remark.
On some sides, I found this speech quite historic, said Mr. Gingrich, interviewed on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former president, considered by some to be a possible candidate for the Republican nomination for the 2012 presidential election, said he was delighted to have seen "a left-wing president" remind members of the Nobel Committee "that they would not be free and could not award a peace prize if the use of force did not exist".
For Michael Gerson, former George W. Bush columnist and Washington Post columnist, Obama delivered "a very American speech."
In addition to presenting himself as a “citizen of the world” as “he always does,” he “spoke like an American president,” reminding Europeans “that they live in a security bubble that they haven’t created and that they don’t do much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
Among the few on the right not to be convinced, a Bush-era hawk, former UN ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "dull, blistering and uninspired" on the National Review Online site.
To the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When one wraps war in the notion of justice, one can easily justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
The centre-left press, however, remained commendable to the president.
The Los Angeles Times, while continuing to believe that the Nobel Prize was awarded prematurely to Mr. Obama, called his speech "overproduction" even for a speaker known for his talent.
The Oslo speech “should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions against conflict, poverty and oppression,” the California daily said.
Obama “pronounced the right speech,” the New York Times said, calling him “both dark and uplifting.”
Routiers: three marathons for an agreement that saves Christmas supplies
After three marathon-negotiation sessions, the road trade unions and TLF, the only employers' organization to remain until the end, reached an agreement on Friday night that ends the strike slogan and the threat to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "rejoiced" about this agreement, after several negotiating sessions, which began Wednesday morning.
After a second night of talks, the negotiators left early on Friday, hoping to sign the agreement early in the morning.
And this even if three employers' organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) had knocked on the door.
But it took even more than six hours of a meeting that began at 11:00 a.m. for everyone to agree and the text to be signed by 6:00 p.m.
The conflict “would have been very detrimental to businesses” and “there was a fear that it would disrupt the holidays,” Bussereau said.
The text foresees an increase in wages of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and of 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
In hourly rate, for low-wages, "we go from 8.72 euros to 9.06.
It's not much, but we're starting from very far away, explained Patrice Clos (FO).
Either we will give the order to our activists that there are no blockades, no blockades of the supply centers.
But we can always have some recalcitrants who are not happy, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of TLF, hailed "a good deal", although it was "difficult to grant increases on high wages given international competition".
According to him, the increases will be of the order of 170 euros per month for low wages and from 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is the agreement of common sense and respect for employees, said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) hailed "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) called for an “acceptable compromise”.
The agreement also provides for the revaluation of travel costs by 3%, and the general state of road transport in the first half of 2010, which will allow in particular to address the issue of a 13th month and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Mr Bussereau recalled that "a reduction of 100 million euros in employers' charges" was the subject of a government amendment to the draft amending finance law for 2009, voted on the night of Thursday to Friday by the National Assembly.
The government will ask the Senate to vote on it "in identical terms".
The signature of TLF allows the agreement to apply first to the companies that are members of this organization, and secondly, to the entire profession, in case of extension by the Minister of Labour.
It will be done "as soon as possible," Bussereau said.
Opposition from employers' organizations can only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced a "market of fools", because the 100 million euros "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for part of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport has forced us to negotiate urgently, not in conclusion of a shared analysis, but in order not to upset the turkey eaters of the next New Year's Eve, deplored the Unostra.
For the Other, the agreement risks "digging the grave of a very large number of SMEs in the sector in the next 12 months".
RER A: disturbances this weekend, unions unhappy with the proposals of the RATP
The disruptions on the RER A, France's largest urban public transit line, will continue over the weekend, as a meeting on Friday on the second day of strike between unions and RATP management left them hungry for their demand for premiums.
