Turkish Justice Dissolves Pro-Kurdish Party, Decision With Consequences
Turkey’s Constitutional Court on Friday ruled the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that was immediately followed by angry outbursts in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision is likely to greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just reached out to the Kurdish community to try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for a Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it had become a "focus of activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," the president of the court, Hasim Kiliç, told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision was taken unanimously by the 11 judges, while a qualified majority of seven votes was required to pronounce the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's cadres, including its chairman Ahmet Türk and lawmaker Aysel Tugluk, are banned from political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity for Mr. Türk and Ms. Tugluk and the confiscation by the Treasury of the party's assets.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders had warned before the verdict that MPs would leave Parliament rather than sit as unlabeled MPs.
The decision follows a 2007 case by Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya, who accused the DTP of obeying the "directives" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party, however, says it has "no organic ties" with the PKK but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The Court’s verdict comes as the government has just reached out to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures strengthening its rights, in an attempt to dry up Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
DTP leaders said a dissolution could lead to a rise in tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where numerous protests against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan have escalated into clashes with police in recent weeks.
As soon as justice was announced, a thousand protesters gathered outside the DTP's premises in Diyarbakir, the large city in the southeast mostly populated by Kurds.
Police fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while protesters threw molotov cocktails or stones, with slingshots.
A hundred people also protested in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk said the court’s decision would “deepen despair.”
Turkey cannot resolve this issue by banning a party, he told reporters.
The government, formed by a party from the Islamist movement, also deplored the decision.
We are in principle opposed to the closure of parties.
That doesn’t solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a total torpedo of the democratic opening launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can, of course, expect a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the deadliest in recent months.
The first snow can fall.
What Wolfgang Brauburger wants is a very harsh winter.
But the head of the clearing and sandblasting service of the roads (FES) makes clear that it is not to annoy the citizens.
This is simply so that the agents can test the technique of the vehicles and learn to master them well.
And according to the meteorologists, it could be for this weekend.
More than 300 officers and 120 vehicles stand ready to tackle snow and ice.
The EDF follows a very elaborate plan.
Mr. Brauburger explains that as soon as it starts to snow on the city of Frankfurt and temperatures drop below zero, large sandblasting vehicles travel along 20 main routes (called routes A).
This includes high-traffic streets, major arteries, such as the Neue Weg and Hanauer Landstraße.
Also included are fire accesses, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloping streets such as Atzelbergstraße.
EDF officers begin their service at three o'clock in the morning.
If necessary, the 1040 kilometers of road must be salted with a road fondant that adheres well, in a maximum of 3 hours.
This is why the EDF service starts at 3am "so that the roads are cleared when the daily migration traffic begins".
Where it gets harder is when the snow starts to fall at 7:30 in the morning.
This poses problems, says the head of the clearing and sandblasting service of the roads "because no motorist is willing to let the salting vehicles pass".
Then, if it does not snow, we take care of access roads and service roads - such as the Rat-Beil-Straße.
Secondary lanes and side streets come last.
Mr. Brauburger is well aware that this always causes some complaints.
At five o'clock in the morning, the EDF pedestrian team set out to first clear areas deemed hazardous and crossings.
As for cycle paths, the EDF services are generally unable to deal with them.
Mr. Brauburger said that there was a special service in Frankfurt to monitor the condition of the bridges between 10 p.m. and 4.30 a.m.
As ice forms very quickly on these surfaces, salting vehicles intervene as soon as the temperature drops below 2 degrees.
The police may also use this special service for snacks when needed.
The Cradle of Dinosaurs
The Tawa hallae resembled other carnivorous dinosaurs: this biped was about 2 meters long by 1.50m tall, its hind limbs were powerful, its elongated skull was provided with sharp, curved teeth, its short arms ended in sickle claws and it had a long tail.
If this species had lived a few million years later, it would have had nothing exceptional.
But, as Sertling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and his colleagues report in Thursday’s Science magazine, the Tawa hallae is one of the first dinosaurs with these morphological features.
This animal lived 215 million years ago in New Mexico, which at the time was part of the landmass of the supercontinent, Pangaea, and was near the equator.
Sertling Nesbitt says that the discovery of the Tawa illuminates a new day in the evolution of the first dinosaurs.
Indeed, it informs us about the kinship links, the distribution and the characteristics of the latter.
It was in 2006 that Sertling Nesbitt undertook excavations with other paleontologists at the Gohst Ranch site in northern New Mexico.
Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History and member of the excavation team says that they sometimes found a dozen bones in a day which is absolutely unique for a sedimentary layer dating back to the Triassic.
Scientists soon realized that some of these bones belonged to a new species.
Excavations have found the remains of five specimens.
A discovery that confirms theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
Researchers named it Tawa after the Hopi Indian word for the sun god.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an exceptional discovery: dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare and are limited to a few incomplete bone fragments.
Not all paleontologists share this enthusiasm.
For example, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn does not find this discovery to be particularly spectacular, but he points out that it confirms some theories regarding the early evolution of dinosaurs.
According to the current state of knowledge, dinosaurs appeared on Earth about 230 million years ago.
Most of the oldest fossils, however, are fragmented and incomplete, making it very difficult to classify the earliest dinosaurs.
Experts wonder, among other things, at what time the saurians were divided into three major groups of evolution: the theropods (carnivores) which include the tyrannosaur and the velociraptor which appeared later and from which descend the birds, the sauropods, quadrupeds with long necks, and those related to them and the herbivores ornithischians such as the particiens.
According to the studies of S. Nesbitt and his colleagues, the Tawa is one of the earliest theropods.
This species has an interesting relationship of both primitive and developed characteristics, says S. Nesbitt.
Researchers have found clues that suggest that the Tawa hallae possessed small air sacs in its bones at the level of the skull, just like birds that are the descendants of theropods.
These small pockets of air make it easier for birds to breathe compared to mammals.
It appears that in the Tawa hallae, the vertebrae were also partially filled with air.
According to Randall Irmis, the Tawa is one of the oldest theropods with small air sacs in its bones.
As the related lineage of the huge sauropods also possessed aerial sacs and a light frame, it can be thought that their common ancestor already had this beneficial innovation.
Three successive waves of migration to North America.
As the most primitive dinosaurs known lived in South America, the researchers concluded that the saurians had appeared there.
As a result, the three major evolutionary lines split and spread from South America to the rest of the world, i.e., all of the landmasses that formed the supercontinent Pangaea.
This seems to be confirmed by the fact that the team of paleontologists has also discovered the remains of two other theropods that are not particularly related to it.
All three species cannot be descended from a common ancestor who migrated, the researchers say.
Alan Turner of the New York Museum of Natural History and co-author of Science Studies magazine says there have been at least three waves of migration to North America.
There are, of course, some contradictions.
Martin Sander, a paleontologist in Bonn, says there is an even older species, the silesaur, which lived in present-day Poland and belongs to a group related to dinosaurs.
According to him, this could give a mistaken view because there are a large number of dinosaur fossils in South America that have been preserved while virtually none are found on other continents.
On the other hand, how dinosaurs managed to become the dominant tetrapod of the secondary era when they came from a relatively rare collateral line of the reptilian branch, remains a mystery today.
In Triassic times, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of modern crocodiles and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread throughout the planet thus favoring the development of many new species while others, which were related to them, disappeared between the Triassic and the Jurassic.
Such a success, however, is not eternal.
To explain this transformation, Martin Sander sees two hypotheses.
There may have been a mass extinction to which dinosaurs survived randomly while other reptiles reportedly went extinct.
Or else, the dinosaurs were better suited and so they were able to eliminate competition on the ground.
In any case, such success is not eternal.
150 million years later, the fall of a meteorite favored the flourishing of a group of animals that had also developed during the Triassic and that since that time had been vegetating in the shadows: these were mammals.
Vienna Solidarity in Sao Paulo
The list is long and there are signatories from all over the world.
There are those of professors from the University of Toronto, the University of Cambridge, the University of Vienna or Berkeley in California.
There are those of lecturers from the University of Naples, Quebec City, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen.
The evacuation by the police of the J.W. Goethe University casino in Frankfurt is making waves all over the planet.
278 professors and professors from J.W. Goethe University and other higher education institutions in Germany, Europe, North and South America express their solidarity with the protesting students of the Westend Campus.
