75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for young generation women who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study "Fertility and professional career of women in Spain", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have had their careers limited because of motherhood.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life as a couple and the number of children, whether the woman works or not and the type of employment occupied.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or have an unstable job, get into a relationship earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are pushing back on entry into couple life and first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women aged 35-49 with fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after moving in as a couple. This figure rises to 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to postpone the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised largely influences maternity, but less the date of start of common life," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the gap between the age of marriage of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who had completed elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 and 32.1 years of age, respectively.
“Another distinction also appears between women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education get married and have their first child before finding a stable job, those who have completed middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a prerequisite for marriage and the arrival of a child, "says Ms. Delgado.
