The aim of this initiative is to raise awareness of the importance of wearing a helmet, since it is the only protective element to prevent head injuries, or even death, in the event of a two-wheeled accident.
Michelin said the campaign was in line with its commitment to road safety, which “goes beyond designing and manufacturing ever safer products” and said it contributed to this goal through other educational and informative actions.
This new campaign to encourage the wearing of the helmet on two wheels, under the motto "To be or not to be", will include a first phase during which posters will be distributed in more than 500 motorcycle garages, in order to guarantee the widest diffusion.
Finally, Michelin stressed that road safety "is a constant concern" for the company, because as a manufacturer of tires for two-wheeled vehicles, one of its main objectives is to develop products that are always safer.
Sales of light commercial vehicles are growing
After almost two years, the light commercial vehicle market is starting to see some light at the end of the tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in November in Spain represent an increase of 12.6% compared to 2008 and, more importantly, they represent the first increase after 22 consecutive months of decrease, according to the figures of the employers' union of manufacturers Anfac and Ganvam, that of dealers.
The good news, however, should be nuanced, since the reference for comparison, November 2008, was particularly bad, with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
As a result, despite the upturn last month, the registrations accumulated during these 11 months are 40% below those of the previous year.
Since January, if all vehicles that fall into the light commercial vehicle category (passenger car derivatives, pick-ups, vans, light vans and light chassis trucks) are added, 95,853 have been sold.
The large clouds that most affect their demand have not dissipated because, although they are also purchased by individuals, most purchases are made by small or medium-sized companies, which pay almost 100% of the time through external financing.
Thus, in addition to the constraints implied by the limitation of bank credits, other factors must be added such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
In the face of this situation and unlike passenger vehicles, aid for the purchase of the 2000E has been of little use.
In addition to individuals, freelancers and SMEs who wish to acquire a light commercial vehicle of less than 3.5 tonnes with a level of CO2 emissions that does not exceed 160 grams per kilometer, can also benefit, but the number of operations speaks for itself.
Yesterday, at Ganvam, the need for the administration to pay particular attention to these vehicles and also to commercial vehicles (trucks and buses) was once again recalled.
The dealers association foresees a year 2010 similar to the one that ends, for which it calculates a drop in sales (of passenger vehicles and 4x4) of 19%.
Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as will be the case with the ESP stability control, emergency braking systems will be a mandatory element on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a shortage period has been set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, although, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing the pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the kick given by the driver.
But the latter does not always maintain the pressure until the end.
According to a study conducted by car components manufacturer Bosch, one-third of drivers involved in an accident had not been able to press the brake before the collision, and half of them had not taken advantage of its full strength.
Up to 1100 accidents
The intervention of the help, in revenge, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance that the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with this type of element, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even greater with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to a radar or camera, detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum stress on the brakes in order to minimize damage.
