How much should you be paid based on your Facebook profile?
Facebook users can know the salary they would deserve based on their profile, thanks to a new application from Trovit, the search engine with the largest number of real estate, job and vehicle listings in Spain.
The “How much should you get paid?” tool calculates users’ salaries from the more than 140,000 job offers that Trovit has in Spain, from a form available on Facebook, where you need to register your profession, your years of experience, your age and the city where you want to work.
For a week that the application has been working, the search engine has detected that as a rule, the Spanish worker "feels poorly paid", explained in a statement the head of products of Trovit, Albert Ribera.
According to the data available to Trovità from its search engines in the United Kingdom and France, Spaniards are the least well paid.
A British computer programmer receives 45,226 euros gross annually and a French one, 31,059, while a Spaniard receives 24,000 euros.
Similarly, a driver receives 34,247 euros gross per year in England, 25,751 in France and 16,420 in Spain.
According to Trovit, the least well-paid job in Spain is as a waiter, with 11,592 euros net per year, followed by a salesman, with 14,725 euros, and a worker, with 15,667 euros.
The most sought-after jobs on the Internet in the last three months are driver, part-time and social worker jobs.
Brazil sets a date for Zelaya's departure
The Brazilian government has set a deadline for Manuel Zelaya to stay at his embassy in Tegucigalpa.
The overthrown president must abandon the diplomatic legation by January 27, 2010, the date of the official end of his term.
Francisco Catunda, the businessman of the Brazilian embassy in the capital of Honduras, confirmed to TV Globo that “Mel” knows he must leave the embassy, where he has been a refugee since September 21, before that date.
“He is aware that he must leave on January 27, at the end of his mandate, he must look for another destination.”
The channel also quoted the former official, who confirmed his intention to leave the embassy before the deadline: "My position is to leave as soon as possible, logically with the support of the Brazilian government," Zelaya said by phone.
After the November 29 elections (in which Porfirio Lobo was elected), Zelaya assured that he would remain in the Brazilian embassy until January.
However, the same week, he tried to seek refuge in Brazil.
The operation ultimately failed, as Zelaya refused the condition of political exile that the de facto government presided over by Roberto Micheletti intended to impose on him.
Thank you very much
After rosy days since last spring, during which asset inflation was the dominant rating in the markets, uncertainty emerges again, which is not surprising since it is their natural state, in an environment where agents make decisions about a future that is by nature uncertain.
The remedy used by central banks to stabilize markets has been to monetize debt through the direct purchase of assets and indirectly by giving abundant liquidity at rates close to zero, so that financial institutions buy assets to mobilize.
Central banks have already confirmed that direct asset purchases have been virtually finalized and, without questioning their non-conformist liquidity policy, are starting to put some sand in the cogs, as did the ECB, with their one-year auction next week.
As a result, investors doubt the ability of the global economy to maintain an economic recovery without heterodox measures, and we are witnessing a reversal in the reduction of risk premiums.
Stock market volatility and corporate bond spreads are rising again, although they remain very far from the paranormal levels they reached at the beginning of the year.
States have been forced to socialize private risk and public debt is again affected.
There is once again a flight towards quality and the US, Japan and Germany have been the havens chosen by investors, causing a widening of the differences between the countries of the euro area and Germany.
Spain was hardly affected by this episode of instability, but then Standard & Poor's threatened a further downward revision of the rating of the Kingdom of Spain.
On the other hand, a little uncertainty is not bad for silencing moral risk advocates, who were again trying to provoke a case of conscience among those responsible for global economic policy that had restrained the destructive effects derived from the credit limitation on the destruction of employment, when what would have to be done is decree a new day of grace.
However, the situation in Dubai resembles a tribal struggle between the emirs to give back its place in power in the emirates and we have already seen the case of Greece.
A government that hides a public deficit, elections, and a new government that discovers the pot of roses.
Prodi did it in Italy after Berlusconi and Socrates in Portugal after Durão Barroso.
It would be perfectly irrational for Ecofin to save Hungary from non-compliance with its external payments at the beginning of the year and allow a euro area country to fail to meet its commitments.
On the other hand, what makes sense is that Ecofin has encouraged the Greek government to be transparent and makes its citizens co-responsible for the need for extraordinary measures to maintain the stability of its public finances.
If, as we hope, we find ourselves facing an episode of normalization of transient risk premiums, after a few excesses in high positions, that would be predictable.
In the Spanish case, as long as our gaps in public debt increase to the extent of European corporate bonds, we do not have to worry.
If European gaps narrowed and ours continued to increase, it would be an idiosyncratic Spanish risk.
The Standard & Poor's case is an anecdote: when our forecasting indicators force most survey services to anticipate their stimulus models and revise upwards their 2011 forecasts, with the OECD and the European Commission also coming back to charge with a Japanese model for the Spanish economy, it does not augur much hope for their warning.
